{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Jup7TBhvWLs1knYQrYDpXT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for this product search REST API system that uses embeddings, vector search, and LLM re-ranking.\n\nThe system has:\n1. REST API endpoint\n2. Embedding model (converts query → vector)\n3. Vector database (similarity search)\n4. LLM re-ranker (reorders results)\n\nI need to think about what the minimum test level is for catching real failures for each behavior.\n\n**BEHAVIOR 1: Embedding vector dimensionality**\n- What: The embedding vector produced for a query string has correct dimensionality for the vector database index\n- Real failure scenario: Vector has wrong dimension → vector DB rejects it or returns garbage\n- Mock-miss question: Could I mock the embedding model and miss this? YES. If I mock the embedding model to return a vector of any dimension, I won't catch the real embedding model producing wrong dimension.\n- Real infra: The embedding model is a real external service/API. I can't know what dimension it produces without calling it.\n- Dependency: The embedding model (could be OpenAI, local transformer, etc.) needs to be called with a real query to check actual output dimension.\n- Level: Must be **Integration** at minimum - need to call the real embedding model to get a real vector, then verify its dimension. Even better, **Agentic** if the embedding model is an LLM-based service (like OpenAI embeddings) where the dimension is a model-level contract that could change.\n- Actually, thinking more carefully: The embedding model dimension is typically a fixed contract from that model (e.g., text-embedding-3-small is 1536 dim). It's deterministic. Calling it 100 times gives the same dimension. So it's not truly Agentic (which implies non-determinism/variance).\n- But do I need the real embedding model or can I mock it? The whole point is \"does the vector I produce have the right dimension?\" If I mock the embedding, I lose the real dependency. \n\nThe real embedding model must be invoked to catch dimension mismatches—whether from model changes, vector DB schema updates, or code transformation bugs. This requires Integration-level testing with actual calls to the embedding service, not mocks.\n\nThe embedding model is likely a remote API (OpenAI or similar), pushing this to System level since real HTTP calls are involved. The vector DB could be local or remote, but for testing I'd call the actual embedding API and insert vectors into a test database instance, then verify dimensions align. The critical failure boundary is the embedding model API itself, so System-level testing is appropriate.\n\nFor similarity search, the real failure mode is unsorted or incorrectly sorted results—the system must return matches ordered by descending cosine similarity scores.\n\nMocking the vector DB won't catch sorting bugs in the actual code path. I need a real vector DB instance (even in-memory) with actual test data to verify the search returns properly ordered results. This is Integration-level since it requires the real vector DB contract and behavior, not just mocked responses. Unit testing with mocks would pass even if the sorting logic never executes, so the real infrastructure is essential here.\n\nFor the LLM re-ranking behavior, the core issue is different. The real LLM's judgment about contextual relevance is what matters—mocking it would hide whether the actual model reorders results correctly for nuanced queries. This depends on the LLM's actual capabilities, so I need the real model to validate the re-ranking behavior works as intended.\n\nThe query-with-no-matches case is simpler: it should return an empty set rather than low-quality noise.\n\nMocking the vector DB won't work here because I need to verify the actual filtering logic—if the real database returns results or the threshold check is missing, a mock won't catch that. I need the real vector DB to confirm it properly filters out low-relevance matches. This is deterministic behavior with no LLM dependency, so it's an **Integration** test: spin up a real vector DB instance with test data, query for something nonexistent, and verify the result is empty.\n\nFor latency, the requirement is that the full pipeline completes in under 2 seconds on a typical case. Mocking everything would hide real performance bottlenecks, so I need to measure against actual infrastructure. Agentic behavior depends on real LLM non-determinism, while workflow encompasses multiple sequential agentic steps.\n\nFor embedding dimensionality, the key question is whether the embedding model itself is a real HTTP API or a local service. If it's cloud-based, this becomes a System-level test since I need the actual API call. If it's local and mockable, Integration suffices. The real failure mode occurs when embedding dimensions don't match the vector database schema, so both components must be genuine. Most embedding models are cloud APIs, making this System-level, though the core requirement is validating that query embeddings align with the indexed vector dimensions.\n\nThe failure boundary is clear: call the embedding service, receive a vector, verify it's compatible with the database index. Mocking the embedding model defeats the purpose since I'd lose the real dependency. This pushes the minimum level to System. Unit testing can't work without actual embedding output. Integration might work if the embedding service is local and testable. System is most likely since embedding APIs are typically external. The behavior itself—ensuring correct vector dimensionality—isn't about LLM non-determinism or multi-step workflows, so Agentic and Workflow levels don't apply.\n\nThe real question is what causes the failure: either the embedding model outputs an unexpected dimension (though models typically have fixed output sizes), or the vector database index expects a different dimension than what's being provided.\n\nTo catch actual failures in code or configuration, I need the real embedding model call (or a test double matching its documented output shape) and the real vector database (or a test instance with actual configuration). Mocking the embedding to always return 1536 dimensions could hide real problems—like the actual model returning 1536 but the database expecting 768, or code incorrectly transforming 1536 to 1024, or missing shape validation entirely. Testing requires the real embedding API and a real vector database instance, making this fundamentally a System-level test since the external embedding API is the limiting factor.\n\nFor the LLM re-ranking behavior, the core question is whether the real LLM actually reorders results based on nuanced intent. This requires calling the actual LLM with real queries and results to verify it changes the order appropriately. Mocking the LLM to always reorder would mask whether it's being called at all or whether it's reordering incorrectly. Since the behavior depends on real LLM judgment, which is non-deterministic, this is an Agentic-level test.\n\nHowever, there's a nuance here: with temperature=0 and identical inputs, the same LLM version should produce consistent outputs across multiple runs. The variability comes from different LLM versions, prompt changes, or input variations. The test itself—checking if the LLM reorders for nuanced queries—still requires the real model to validate that the nuance-handling actually works as intended. temperature=0.\n- But it does depend on a real LLM call (not a mock).\n- Is that Agentic? \n\nI think the key distinction is:\n- Agentic: The test is verifying behavior that only a real LLM can provide, even if it's deterministic (with temperature=0)\n- System: The test is verifying behavior that requires real infrastructure (HTTP, subprocess, OS), but the outcome is deterministic\n\nFor behavior 3, the re-ranking is an LLM's judgment. We need the REAL LLM to verify it works. But if temperature=0, the output is deterministic. \n\nActually, I think the definition of Agentic includes \"real AI/ML model call\" even if deterministic. So Agentic is correct.\n\nBut is this **Agentic** or **Workflow**?\n- Workflow: \"multiple agentic steps in sequence, or a full agent pipeline\"\n- This is just one LLM call (reranking), not multiple steps\n\nSo it's **Agentic** (single LLM call for reranking). The question is whether I need to test the full pipeline—embedding, vector search, then LLM reranking—or if I can mock the first two steps and only call the real LLM for the reranking behavior itself. If I mock the embeddings and search results, then verify the LLM reorders them correctly, that's still just one real model call and stays at the Agentic level. The behavior requires comparing two orderings: one from vector similarity and another from LLM reranking. To verify the reranker actually changes the order on nuanced queries, I need both the real vector search results and the real LLM's reranking output.\n\nThe embedding model is an AI/ML call, which could qualify as Agentic, but it's not an LLM. The core failure I'm testing is whether the LLM reranking works, which definitely requires the real LLM. The question is whether I also need the real embedding and vector search, or if I can mock those upstream components and just feed realistic results to the reranker. the real LLM call to verify the reranking actually changes the order. That's Agentic level minimum, though Workflow testing would give more confidence the full pipeline works correctly.\n\nThe core failure I'm trying to catch is whether the LLM reranking step meaningfully reorders results for queries with nuanced intent. To test this, I need to compare the raw vector DB ranking against the LLM-reranked output and confirm they differ. This requires calling the actual LLM, making Agentic the minimum viable level. The reranking behavior is specifically about whether the LLM reranker changes the order of results, not the entire pipeline working end-to-end. This means I need a real LLM reranker to catch failures, making **Agentic** the minimum level. The vector DB can be mocked since I'm only testing the reranking step itself.\n\nFor my final assessment: embedding dimensionality requires calling a real embedding model (likely an API call, so **System** level) to verify the vector dimension is compatible with the database. Similarity ranking order needs a real vector DB instance to confirm the ordering behavior, pointing to **Integration**. The LLM reranking step needs a real LLM reranker to validate it's actually changing the order, which is **Agentic** level.\n\nWhen no matches are found, I need the actual vector DB to verify how it filters low-relevance results, making this **Integration**. End-to-end latency requires the full pipeline running together—embedding API, vector DB, and LLM reranking—so that's **Workflow** level.\n\nLooking at the key questions: embedding dimensionality will definitely fail if I mock the embedding model since I'd miss real dimension mismatches. If the embedding is an API, I need real infrastructure. The embedding model itself isn't LLM-dependent, so this is deterministic. Most likely this is **System** level since embeddings typically come from cloud APIs.\n\nFor similarity ranking order, mocking the vector DB hides ordering bugs entirely. I need the actual DB behavior, which could be local, making this **Integration** level. The ranking is deterministic, not LLM-dependent.\n\nLLM reranking is different—it actually changes the order based on the model's judgment about nuanced intent. Mocking the LLM completely misses reranking bugs. I need real LLM calls, which makes this **Agentic** level.\n\nWhen no matches are found, the system returns empty results. Mocking the vector DB masks filtering bugs, so I need the real DB with its actual threshold behavior. This is **Integration** level, testable locally.\n\nFor end-to-end latency under 2 seconds, mocking everything will always be artificially fast and won't catch real performance issues.\n\nI need all real components—the embedding API, vector DB, and LLM—since latency varies across these dependencies. This requires the **Workflow** level with the full pipeline running end-to-end.\n\nReconsidering behavior 3 about LLM re-ranking: I could test this at the Agentic level alone by just verifying the LLM changes the order for nuanced queries, without running the full pipeline. The key insight is that the test needs to verify the LLM actually reorders results when handling complex queries—not just any reordering, but specifically when vector similarity alone misses the nuanced intent. For approach 1 with mocked results, I'd need to carefully construct a scenario where the vector rankings are ambiguous enough that an LLM would legitimately reorder them. Approach 2 captures this more naturally by using real embeddings and search results that genuinely exhibit this ambiguity. The workflow approach is more convincing because it tests the full pipeline with authentic data that has the properties we're trying to validate.\n\nI'll go with the agentic approach as the minimum viable test, though I recognize the workflow would be more robust.\n\nFor the embedding dimensionality behavior, there are several failure modes to consider. The embedding model could be updated without the code handling the new dimensions, or the database index configuration might expect different dimensions than what the model produces. There could also be shape transformation bugs in the code itself—slicing or padding operations that alter the vector incorrectly. To catch these issues, I need to call the actual embedding model and verify the output dimension matches what the database expects, then test whether the code handles any transformations correctly.\n\nThe key question is whether the embedding model call counts as a System or Integration test. If it's a cloud API like OpenAI, that's clearly System level. If it's a local transformer model, it could be Integration. Assuming a cloud-based embedding service, this would be System level.\n\nLooking at the confidence levels: Unit testing can't catch this (0.0), Integration testing might work if the embedding model is local (0.3), System testing is viable with a cloud API (0.7), and Agentic/Workflow don't apply here (0.0 each).\n\nActually, reviewing the definitions more carefully—System explicitly includes \"real external API call,\" so a cloud embedding API definitely qualifies as System level.\n\nBut wait, Agentic is defined as \"result depends on real LLM non-determinism or a real AI/ML model call.\" Since embeddings are AI/ML models, they might actually fall under Agentic rather than System. The distinction seems to be that System covers deterministic external calls (HTTP, subprocess, OS), while Agentic covers any real AI/ML model invocation, whether deterministic or not. So embedding model calls could reasonably be classified as Agentic level tests. ML models. The guidance specifically mentions \"LLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on what a real LLM produces?\" which points to Agentic being for LLMs specifically, not all AI/ML systems.\n\nLooking at the infrastructure distinction: embedding APIs that call real networks fall under System level, while local embedding models would be Integration. LLM APIs are Agentic since they depend on real LLM outputs. Vector databases could be either System (if using real network) or Integration (if using local test instances).\n\nThis means behavior 1 maps to System or Integration depending on whether the embedding API is remote or local, behavior 2 is Integration with a local vector DB, behavior 3 is Agentic due to LLM reranking, behavior 4 is Integration, and behavior 5 spans multiple levels including Agentic components.\n\nFor behavior 1's confidence levels: Unit is 0.0, Integration is 0.35 if embedding is local, System is 0.65 if embedding is API, Agentic is 0.0, and Workflow is 0.0. The key distinction seems to be that embeddings produce deterministic outputs (same input always yields same output), making them more like System dependencies, whereas LLMs introduce non-determinism through sampling, which is what makes them truly Agentic. So deterministic AI/ML systems like embeddings should be classified as System or Integration based on infrastructure, while non-deterministic ones like LLMs are Agentic. Embeddings are typically deterministic, so this falls at the System or Integration level depending on whether the embedding service is external or local.\n\nNow I'm settling on: Behavior 1 as System (or Integration if using a local embedding), Behavior 2 as Integration, Behavior 3 as Agentic, Behavior 4 as Integration, and Behavior 5 as Workflow. For the probability distributions, Behavior 1 has high confidence at the System level (0.65) with some Integration possibility (0.35) since embeddings could be mocked locally. Behavior 2 requires actual vector search integration to catch ranking bugs, making Integration the dominant level at 0.9 probability.\n\nBehavior 3 depends on real LLM responses for reranking, so Agentic dominates at 0.95. Behavior 4 needs the actual vector database filtering behavior, putting Integration at 0.9 probability. Behavior 5 tests the full pipeline latency constraint, making Workflow the clear choice at 0.9 probability, since individual components won't reveal the complete performance picture. Each distribution sums to 1.0 across all levels.\n\nNow I'll detail the test specifications for each behavior and structure them accordingly.\n\n**BEHAVIOR 1: Embedding Vector Dimensionality**\n- Description: The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index\n- Test: Call the real embedding model with a query, verify the returned vector has the expected dimension (e.g., 1536 for text-embedding-3-small), then verify it can be inserted into and searched in the real vector database index without dimension mismatch errors\n- Minimum level: System\n- Justification: The failure occurs at the boundary between the embedding service (likely a cloud API with real HTTP calls) and the vector database. Mocking the embedding model would hide real dimension mismatches. We need the actual embedding API response to verify compatibility with the actual vector index.\n- Plan-consistent: YES - the test description requires calling the real embedding API (System level).\n\n**BEHAVIOR 2: Similarity Search Result Ordering\n\n**\n- Description: The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score\n- Test: Insert a test vector into the vector database, query with a related vector, extract the similarity scores from the results, and assert that scores are in descending order. Verify this holds for multiple queries with different result set sizes (including single result and empty result edge cases).\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: The failure occurs within the vector database's sorting behavior or the code that retrieves/returns results. Mocking the vector DB would hide real bugs (e.g., code that reverses results, doesn't sort them, or sorts ascending). We need a real vector database (can be a local test instance with real data) to catch sorting bugs.\n- Plan-consistent: YES - the test works with a real vector DB instance.\n\n**BEHAVIOR 3: LLM Re-Ranking Changes Order for Nuanced Queries**\n- Description: The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of results compared to raw similarity scores for queries requiring semantic understanding. Test: Submit queries that benefit from re-ranking (e.g., context-dependent or ambiguous queries), compare the initial similarity-based ordering against the LLM re-ranked ordering, and verify the re-ranked results are semantically more relevant. Validate across multiple query types and result set sizes.\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: Re-ranking behavior depends on the actual LLM's reasoning and the real vector database results. Mocking either component would prevent detection of cases where re-ranking fails to improve ordering or produces unexpected result sequences. A real LLM and vector DB are needed to verify the re-ranking logic works as intended.\n- Plan-consistent: YES - the test uses real LLM and vector DB instances.\n\n**BEHAVIOR 4: No-Match Query Returns Empty Results**\n- Description: A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise\n- Test: Populate the vector database with known vectors. Submit a query (via the embedding and search pipeline) that has a low max similarity score with all database vectors (e.g., a query with completely different semantics). Assert that the result set is empty and does not include results below a configured similarity threshold.\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Justification: The failure occurs at the boundary between the similarity search (which may return low-score results) and the filtering logic (which should exclude them\n\n). Mocking the vector DB would hide failures where the filtering threshold is not applied correctly. We need a real vector database with real search results to verify filtering works.\n- Plan-consistent: YES - the test requires real vector search behavior with configurable thresholds.\n\n**BEHAVIOR 5: End-to-End Latency Below 2 Seconds Median**\n- Description: The end-to-end latency from receiving the REST API query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case\n- Test: Submit the full pipeline (embedding model call → similarity search → LLM re-ranking → return results) with production-like data and measure total latency. Repeat the test 20-50 times with different queries, collect latency measurements, and assert that the median is below 2 seconds. Include both typical queries and complex/nuanced